Solution: I need to find the number of red balls in the second urn.

Let me denote:
- First urn: 8 red, 7 blue (total 15 balls)
- Second urn: x red, 9 blue (total x + 9 balls)

The probability of getting two balls of the same color is the probability of getting two red balls plus the probability of getting two blue balls.

P(same color) = P(both red) + P(both blue)

P(both red) = (8/15) × (x/(x+9))

P(both blue) = (7/15) × (9/(x+9))

So:
$$\frac{8}{15} \cdot \frac{x}{x+9} + \frac{7}{15} \cdot \frac{9}{x+9} = \frac{151}{300}$$

Combining the fractions on the left side:
$$\frac{8x + 63}{15(x+9)} = \frac{151}{300}$$

Cross-multiplying:
$$300(8x + 63) = 151 \cdot 15(x+9)$$

$$300(8x + 63) = 2265(x+9)$$

$$2400x + 18900 = 2265x + 20385$$

$$2400x - 2265x = 20385 - 18900$$

$$135x = 1485$$

$$x = \frac{1485}{135} = 11$$

Let me verify this answer:
- P(both red) = (8/15) × (11/20) = 88/300
- P(both blue) = (7/15) × (9/20) = 63/300
- P(same color) = 88/300 + 63/300 = 151/300 ✓

